Convert Data Convert all character columns into numeric columns except for Restaurant (ID) & Cuisines.However, there are lots of cell with NA data which leads to the next action: filter and get rid of NA data row (this non-NA dataset is used for Model 1 below)

FoodieX$Rating <- as.numeric(as.character(FoodieX$Rating))
NAs introduced by coercion
FoodieX$Votes <- as.numeric(as.character(FoodieX$Votes))
NAs introduced by coercion
FoodieX$Reviews <- as.numeric(as.character(FoodieX$Reviews))
NAs introduced by coercion
trending <- FoodieX[,c('Cuisines','Rating', 'Votes', 'Reviews')]
na_vec <- which(!complete.cases(trending))
#Create a dataset without NA data
model1_data <- trending[-na_vec,]

Model 1: Regression between Rating (dependent variable) & Votes + Review (Independent Variables) Conclusion 2: As we see the adjusted R-squared, only 18% of Ratings is explained by Votes & Reviews. Therefore, the correlation among rating, votes and reviews is insignificant. When we do single linear regression for (Rating & Votes) or (Rating & Reviews), the adjusted R-squares are also lower than 20% -> cannot state the regression

model1 <- lm(Rating ~ Votes+Reviews, data = model1_data)

Conclusion 3: Best Rating Restaurants (4.0 rating) + There are a total 112 restaurants which have a maximum rating of 4.0. Out of 2019 restaurants in the original dataset, this number accounts for 5%. + Among 112 restaurants with 4.0 rating, restaurants serving Indian food account for 35 % (39 restaurants), restaurants serving Chinese food account for 25% (28 restaurants).

Conclusion 4: The popularity of Indian & Chinese Cuisine in Indianapolis All in all, we can say, Indian and Chinese cuisine are the two main parts of Indianapolis restaurant type, accounting for 16.8% and 12.5% of restaurants in Indy (in total). 10% out of each cuisine restaurant serves high quality food and has good customer service as they have 4.0 (maximum) rating. Conclusion 4.1: Indian Cuisine + There are 339 restaurants serving Indian food in Indianapolis (out of 2019 restaurants). However, we only have 39 high quality (rate 4.0) restaurants accounting for only 11.5% Conclusion 4.2: Chinese Cuisine + There are 252 restaurants serving Chinese food in Indianapolis (out of 2019 restaurants). However, we only have 28 high quality (rate 4.0) restaurants accounting for only 11.1%

#Total number of high rate (4.0) restaurants in Indianapolis
high_rate <- filter(model1_data,Rating==4.0)
#Total number of Indian restaurants which has 4.0 rating in Indianapolis
Indian_high_quality <- high_rate %>% select(Cuisines, Votes) %>% filter(str_detect(Cuisines, "Indian")) %>%
  count(Cuisines)
#Total number of Indian restaurants in Indianapolis
Indian_total <- FoodieX %>% select(Cuisines) %>% filter(str_detect(Cuisines, "Indian")) %>%count(Cuisines)
#Total number of Chinese restaurants in Indianapolis
Chinese_total <- FoodieX %>% select(Cuisines) %>% filter(str_detect(Cuisines, "Chinese")) %>%count(Cuisines)
#Total number of Chinese restaurants which has 4.0 rating in Indianapolis
Chinese_high_quality <- high_rate %>% select(Cuisines, Votes) %>% filter(str_detect(Cuisines, "Chinese")) %>% count(Cuisines)
